WHEREAS, Andrew Chambers of New Iberia is a junior at Loreauville High School;
although he was diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes, he is dedicated to helping at-risk teens
through the Teen Court program; after learning that his Acadian, French, and Spanish
ancestors were Revolutionary patriots, he began participating as a reenactor for the
Daughters of the American Revolution America 250 programs; and
WHEREAS, Charlotte Gomes of New Orleans is a senior at Benjamin Franklin High
School; she is passionate about supporting children by volunteering at the University of New
Orleans Children's Library and supporting students across the globe; her efforts have funded
tuition, books, a new dorm, and desks for the Petals School of Africa in Kenya, and she
provided the school with life-changing feminine care supplies; and
WHEREAS, John Parker, Jr., of Bush is a junior at Covington High School; despite
facing significant hearing loss as a toddler, he confidently leads debates, delivers speeches,
and represents youth statewide; he and his sister co-founded The Parker Storylight
Foundation to promote literacy and have collected and distributed more than eight hundred
books to Title I schools and over three hundred blankets during the Christmas season; and
WHEREAS, Maylie Stanley of Glenmora is a senior at Pineville High School and
the Louisiana Teens Speak Up representative through the Epilepsy Foundation; she shares
her personal journey and emphasizes the need for increased research funding, expanded
education, and improved access to care for individuals living with epilepsy, and her
advocacy efforts have included meetings with lawmakers in Washington, D.C.; and
WHEREAS, Brooklynn Warner of Ponchatoula is a junior at Hammond High
Magnet School; she is the oldest sibling in a home that has welcomed children through foster
care, and she understands that potential is often a matter of circumstance; she is the lead
programmer for her robotics teams and was named one of the top forty young women in
computing by the National Center for Women & Information Technology; she also founded
the Pink Potion Society to provide STEM experiences for girls; and
WHEREAS, the 2026 Louisiana Young Heroes are an incredible group of young men
and women who are most deserving of recognition for their outstanding contributions to the
state and its citizens.
